# Oracle MCP Server on OpenShift in tandem with the Red Hat AI Virtual Agent

![sales analyst as a digital AI agent interacting with sales data][image1]

#### Authors

* Sharon Dashet  
* Yuval Turgeman

# Intro

In this blog,  we will show you how to easily deploy and secure the basic [Oracle SQLcl MCP (Model Context Protocol) server](https://docs.oracle.com/en/database/oracle/sql-developer-command-line/25.2/sqcug/using-oracle-sqlcl-mcp-server.html) on a Red Hat OpenShift cluster and how to use it alongside the OpenShift AI platform in a demo AI application, we deploy on OpenShift. This setup allows you to connect Agentic AI applications to an Oracle 23ai Data Warehouse backend. Given that many OpenShift customers rely on Oracle backends for both transactional and analytical requirements, this pattern is expected to be useful immediately.

The Oracle SQLcl MCP server is integrated directly into Oracle‚Äôs core developer tools, primarily via **Oracle SQLcl** (the command-line interface). This native integration allows it to work out-of-the-box with popular environments like the Oracle SQL Developer extension for VS Code. For local testing, adding the local MCP to other popular GenAI-powered IDEs like Cursor is a straightforward configuration.

For example, to add it to your Cursor IDE, the following configuration can be used in the Cursor MCP Settings:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "sqlcl": {
      "command": "/<path>/sqlcl/bin/sql",
      "args": [
        "-mcp"
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

The MCP server also adds special tracing (in the form of table comments and dedicated system tables) that allows DBAs to audit which transactions originated by the agentic AI flows.  
The MCP server current tools can be seen in this screenshot taken from the Cursor local environment:

![][image2]

In the demo most of those tools are being used to connect to the user schema, to run queries and to audit the connections available to the MCP server. Once you have the local configuration in place (plus some saved connections to your Oracle database) you can use the AI Chat (copilot, claude, vs code etc.) to start interacting with the database. In the demo however, we will show how this works in a live environment.

We will employ a hypothetical scenario to illustrate the Oracle MCP server's efficacy in supporting agentic AI use cases. Specifically, this demonstration will focus on the server's capability to convert conversational prompts into standardized SQL transactions for Oracle backends. A sales analyst team would like to use natural language conversational AI to interact with a sales schema in their Oracle 23ai analytical  backend.    
In this use case [Red Hat AI](https://www.redhat.com/en/products/ai) provides the necessary AI infrastructure- including LLMOps and GenAI services like an OpenShift AI vLLM inference service, Guardrails, the [LlamaStack](https://github.com/llamastack/llama-stack) GenAI platform, secure MCP hosting and  RAG backends \- while seamlessly connecting agents to the existing Oracle backends within their Enterprise environment.

For demonstration purposes, we also create a local container of the Oracle 23ai database based on the Oracle registry [free image](https://www.google.com/url?q=https://container-registry.oracle.com/ords/ocr/ba/database/free&sa=D&source=docs&ust=1763065749004151&usg=AOvVaw3P1sQ0ipHnflqGVPgRN7m8).  Of course, for production use cases, we expect to connect the MCP server to a real instance serving analytical and transactional workloads on the Enterprise host environments such as Oracle OCI, on-premise or on a public cloud. In reality most of these instances would probably be a read only replica to mitigate LLM risks and protected heavily with Oracle RBAC and other measures. In our demo we use a read only user to mimic access to a sales schema.   As we will show in the [Setup](#setup-the-demo) section, we also provide an automation for populating the database with the [TPC-DS benchmark](https://medium.com/hyrise/a-summary-of-tpc-ds-9fb5e7339a35) data. TPC-DS (Transaction Processing Performance Council \- Decision Support) is a benchmark for decision support systems with a schema that includes tables such as store\_sales, web\_sales, catalog\_sales, customer, item, and date\_dim. These standardized queries are designed to simulate real-world business analytics workloads.

To showcase this integration, we will use this demo AI application:  [AI Virtual Agent.](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-virtual-agent)   The AI Virtual Agent showcases how we utilize OpenShift and OpenShift AI to build an immersive AI Agent builder utilizing AI infrastructures on a secured Kubernetes cluster. While OpenShift AI provides the AI infrastructure, OpenShift is the Application platform where you can deploy and scale the AI agents in your environments just like with any microservice.For ensuring only authorized and authenticated users are interacting with the database, we utilize both Oracle native RBAC and OpenShift container platform security primitives. The local MCP server is deployed as an OpenShift container exposing the remote Streamable-HTTP interface.

The sales analysts  will be able to use the AI Virtual Agent to send prompts like: ‚Äúshow me the top selling product in the last quarter in each geography‚Äù. Their natural language prompts are translated to SQL using the AI application LLM and then passed to Oracle via one of the MCP tooling (Run SQL etc.).  
This is a high level conceptual depiction of the demo architecture:

![][image3]

**OpenShift** is where you deploy your AI applications (**AI Virtual Agent** in our example), **OpenShift AI** is where you can deploy your LLMs using GPU nodes while an **Oracle MCP server** on OpenShift connects your AI application to an existing Oracle database.

# Setup the Demo {#setup-the-demo}

## Requirements and Setup

First, make sure to meet the minimum requirements listed in the [AI Virtual Agent Readme file](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-virtual-agent), you will find them under the requirements section.  The two main requirements are an OpenShift Cluster with OpenShift AI.   
If you host your models in OpenShift AI, for the LLM model choice we recommend  using one of these models: llama-3-1-8b-instruct for simple queries or gpt-oss-20b for more complex queries. The models will be deployed on OpenShift GPU nodes so make sure you have a GPU to match your model choice.  
The demo setup will provision the model as an OpenShift AI vLLM service; however if you don‚Äôt have GPU nodes in your OpenShift cluster you can use Gemini on GCP Vertex AI to power the AI Virtual Agent. This is the only demo resource that is provisioned  remotely to the OpenShift cluster.

In our [demo](#demo-of-red-hat-ai-virtual-agent-and-oracle-mcp) chapter we show how to use the integration of gpt-oss-20b with vLLM (using NVIDIA L40S), we also tested this setup with gemini-2.5-flash on GCP Vertex AI.

The easiest way to deploy the AI Virtual Agent and the Oracle services is to clone the AI Virtual Agent repository and run a simple ‚Äúmake‚Äù command from your local environment.   
The command deploys all the demo resources in a dedicated OpenShift namespace created based on the NAMESPACE variable provided during setup.  
The LLM used  is also set during the setup process based on the LLM variable.  
The main services provisioned in the dedicated namespace:

* The AI Virtual Agent services and underlying infrastructure (Llama Stack AI gateway, OpenShift AI vLLM inference service, The Agent front-end)  
* Oracle 23ai free database plus two applicative users created for the demo; to mimic the sales team schema and users. We also set the admin passwords and encrypt them as openshift secrets.  
* The Oracle sales schema is populated with a sample of the TPC-DS benchmark data (\~1GB, 25 tables).  
* The Oracle SQLcl MCP server we will connect to the AI Virtual Agent.  
  For convenience we containerized the SQLcl binaries along with a stdio to streamable-http proxy and a startup script.  The image can be found at [quay.io/rh-ai-quickstart/oracle-sqlcl:0.5.11](http://quay.io/rh-ai-quickstart/oracle-sqlcl:0.5.11)  
* Optional remote model endpoint by using the Vertex AI integration.

For a detailed description of the resources that will be deployed in the cluster refer to [Detailed description of the deployed resources](#detailed-description-of-the-deployed-resources).

Alternatively, if you are only interested in the Oracle MCP server on OpenShift (for example if you want to connect it to other  AI applications on OpenShift); we also explain how to install the Oracle MCP server as a standalone service in OpenShift. Refer to [Deploying the Oracle MCP server as a standalone.](#deploying-the-oracle-mcp-server-as-a-standalone)

## Deploying the demo

* Clone the [AI Virtual Agent](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-virtual-agent) repository to a local folder and navigate to the setup folder.  In the following shell script we set up the demo with a vLLM inference service on OpenShift AI. The model we use is gpt-oss-20b on the NVIDIA L40S GPU.

```shell
# clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-virtual-agent.git

# Navigate to cluster deployment directory
cd deploy/cluster

# Deploy with the ORACELE option

make install NAMESPACE=<your openshift namespace> \
LLM=gpt-oss-20b LLM_TOLERATION=g6-gpu ORACLE=true

# Note - LLM_TOLERATION is needed for tainted GPU nodes

```

* When using GCP model hosting instead of OpenShift AI vLLM run this command instead (we assume you have Gemini endpoint deployed on GPC Vertex AI):

```shell

# Deploy with Oracle with remote model on Vertex AI

make install NAMESPACE=<your openshit namespace> ORACLE=true  \
GCP_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_FILE=<your GCP service account json file> \
VERTEX_AI_PROJECT=<your gcp project id>  \
VERTEX_AI_LOCATION=<your gcp region>

```

## Verifying the deployment

Wait about 20 minutes for the resources to be deployed (TPC-DS data population takes the majority of time) by the automation and run this OC commands to make sure everything is ready for demo time:

```shell
# All Oracle resources
oc get all -l app.kubernetes.io/name=oracle-db -n ai-demo

# Secrets
oc get secrets -l app.kubernetes.io/component=user-secret -n ai-demo

# TPC-DS job completed
oc get job oracle-db-tpcds-populate -n ai-demo
# Expected: COMPLETIONS 1/1

# MCP server
oc get service -l app.kubernetes.io/component=mcp-server -n ai-demo

```

After all resources are ready, jump right into the [demo section](#demo-of-red-hat-ai-virtual-agent-and-oracle-mcp) and start building agents with the Oracle MCP server.

## Deploying the Oracle MCP server as a standalone {#deploying-the-oracle-mcp-server-as-a-standalone}

If you only want to test the Oracle MCP Server on OpenShift you can use these helm charts:

1. For the Oracle local free database container: [https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-architecture-charts/tree/main/oracle-db](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-architecture-charts/tree/main/oracle-db)  
2. For the Oracle MCP server on OpenShift  container : [https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-architecture-charts/tree/main/mcp-servers](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-architecture-charts/tree/main/mcp-servers)

## Detailed description of the deployed resources  {#detailed-description-of-the-deployed-resources}

1. AI Virtual Agent service:
   - Run this openshift cli command to get the public route to the AI Virtual Agent UI: 

   ```shell
   oc get routes ai-virtual-agent-authenticated -o \ jsonpath='{.status.ingress[0].host}'
   ```

2. Oracle 23ai as a local container:
   - Pod: oracle-db-0 (StatefulSet)
   - Image: container-registry.oracle.com/database/free:23.5.0.0
   - Storage: 10Gi PVC
   - Service: oracle-db:1521/freepdb1  
    
3. Database Users (Auto-Created)

   Three users with auto-generated passwords as Kubernetes secrets:

   | User | Schema | Mode | Purpose | Secret Name |
   | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
   | system | system | RW | Admin | oracle-db-user-system |
   | sales | sales | RW | Data owner | oracle-db-user-sales |
   | sales\_reader | sales | RO | MCP/AI access | oracle-db-user-sales-reader |

   Secret contains: username, password, host, port, serviceName, jdbc-uri, connection-string
   In our demo, we will save the read only sales\_reader in the MCP container to avoid transactions that might change the database.

4. TPC-DS Benchmark Data
   - Job: oracle-db-tpcds-populate
   - Tables: 25 tables (customers, sales, inventory, stores)
   - Volume: \~1GB, \~2.8M rows in store\_sales
   - Load time: 15-20 minutes  
5. Oracle MCP Server (oracle-sqlcl)
   - Image: quay.io/rh-ai-quickstart/oracle-sqlcl:0.5.11
   - Transport: stdio ‚Üí Streamable-HTTP
   - Endpoint: http://mcp-oracle-sqlcl:8080/mcp
   - Tools: run\_sql, list\_connections, etc

# Demo Time

## Demo of Red Hat AI Virtual Agent and Oracle MCP {#demo-of-red-hat-ai-virtual-agent-and-oracle-mcp}

Now that we have provisioned all the demo resources, it‚Äôs time to actually use the Oracle MCP server from the AI Virtual Agent studio and help our sales analysts on their daily tasks\!

After deploying the AI Virtual Agent platform to OpenShift,  you need to configure the admin user credentials (username and email matching your OpenShift account).

```shell
$ make install NAMESPACE=ai-demo LLM=gpt-oss-20b LLM_TOLERATION=g6-gpu ORACLE=true
Updating Helm dependencies
üîß Collecting environment variables for AI Virtual Agent deployment...

Enter admin user name: your-openshift-username
Enter admin user email: your-openshift-email

üí° Tavily Search API Key
     Without a key, web search capabilities will be disabled in your AI agents.
     To enable web search, obtain a key from https://tavily.com/

Enter Tavily API Key now (or press Enter to continue without web search): tvly-XXXXXXXX
```

Access the application through the OpenShift public route:

```shell
oc get routes ai-virtual-agent-authenticated -o jsonpath='{.status.ingress[0].host}'
```

The platform uses OpenShift OAuth for authentication, so you'll be automatically logged in with your OpenShift credentials.

### MCP Server Discovery and Registration

First we will register the Oracle MCP server in the AI Virtual Agent studio:

**![][image4]**

The platform automatically discovers MCP servers deployed in the same OpenShift namespace by scanning for Kubernetes services with the label app.kubernetes.io/component=mcp-server. This label is automatically added by the mcp-servers Helm chart from [rh-ai-quickstart/ai-architecture-charts](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-architecture-charts) when deploying MCP servers. This screenshot shows the MCP Servers tab where the mcp-oracle-sqlcl server has been auto-discovered from the namespace. The interface displays the server's connection details (service name, port) and provides the ability to register it with LlamaStack, making its tools available to AI agents.

### Creating the Oracle Sales Analyst Agent

Once the MCP server is connected to the platform we can easily create an Agent for our sales analysts.

**![][image5]**

This screenshot shows the agent creation interface with the following configuration:

- Agent Name: oracle-sales  
- Model: gpt-oss-20b (hosted in the same namespace using vLLM as inference service)  
- MCP Server: mcp-oracle-sqlcl (discovered and registered with LlamaStack in the previous step)  
- System Prompt:  ‚ÄúYou are a helpful sales data analyst assistant with access to an Oracle database containing TPC-DS benchmark data. When answering questions: use ORACLE SQL queries to retrieve accurate data from the database. Present your queries and results in a clear, business-friendly format. If you need to explore the schema, use your tools to describe tables first. Always use the sales\_reader connection which has read-only access to the sales schema.‚Äù

The agent is configured to use Oracle-specific SQL syntax and work with the TPC-DS benchmark schema through the read-only sales\_reader connection.

# Known Limitations

Vertex AI integration in Llama Stack 0.3.2 (the version used in our demo) is [broken](https://github.com/llamastack/llama-stack/pull/4041)\-  we expect it to be fixed on the next upstream version of Llama Stack.

# Wrapping Up

In this blog, we showed an automation for securely deploying the basic [Oracle SQLcl MCP (Model Context Protocol) server](https://docs.oracle.com/en/database/oracle/sql-developer-command-line/25.2/sqcug/using-oracle-sqlcl-mcp-server.html) on a Red Hat OpenShift cluster. We demonstrated, using the [AI Virtual Agent](https://github.com/rh-ai-quickstart/ai-virtual-agent) studio, how to use it alongside the OpenShift AI platform in a demo AI application. This setup allows your AI applications to bridge the gap between natural prompts and canonical SQL used to query your Oracle 23ai Data Warehouse backend.
